    body: "Typology differs from allegory in that it respects the historical reality of both the type and the antitype. Adam is a type of Christ (Rom 5:14), the Passover lamb is a type of the Eucharist, the flood is a type of Baptism (1 Pet 3:20-21). Typology rests on the conviction that God, as the Lord of history, orchestrates earlier events to foreshadow later fulfillments. The Catechism (128-130) affirms that typological reading is essential to Catholic exegesis, complementing the literal sense rather than replacing it. Typology also extends forward: present sacramental realities are types of the eschatological fulfillment yet to come.",
