    body: "Theological censures are the negative counterpart to theological notes. They classify the degree to which a proposition departs from Catholic truth. The most severe censure is 'heretical' — directly contradicting a dogma of faith. Lesser censures include 'erroneous' (contradicting a certain theological conclusion), 'close to heresy' (proxima haeresi), 'rash' (temeraria), 'scandalous,' and 'offensive to pious ears' (piarum aurium offensiva). These graduated censures allow the Magisterium to address errors with precision rather than declaring everything either perfectly orthodox or flatly heretical. They were extensively used by the Holy Office and in papal bulls condemning specific propositions.",
