    tags: ["Moral Theology", "Conscience", "Liguori", "Law"],
    oneLiner: "The moral system holding that when a genuinely probable opinion favors liberty (even if the opinion favoring the law is more probable), one may lawfully follow the probable opinion.",
    body: "Developed by the Dominican Bartolomé de Medina in 1577 and later moderated by St. Alphonsus Liguori, probabilism addresses situations of genuine doubt about whether a moral law applies. It holds that a solidly probable opinion — one supported by serious reasons and reputable theologians — may be followed in good conscience even if the opposing opinion (favoring the obligation) is also probable or even more probable. Probabilism avoids both laxism (following any opinion, however flimsy) and rigorism (always following the stricter opinion). It was the dominant moral system in Catholic theology for centuries and continues to influence pastoral practice.",
    example: "If reputable theologians disagree on whether a particular business practice violates justice, a Catholic may follow the solidly probable opinion permitting it, even if more theologians favor the stricter view — this is probabilism in action.",
