    body: "Probabiliorism, favored by many Dominicans, takes a stricter stance than probabilism. It teaches that in cases of moral doubt, one should follow the opinion favoring the moral obligation unless the opinion favoring liberty is clearly more probable. The reasoning is that when the balance of evidence favors the existence of an obligation, prudence requires compliance. Critics argued that probabiliorism was too rigorous and could burden consciences unnecessarily, while defenders maintained it better respected the binding force of moral law. St. Alphonsus Liguori eventually rejected pure probabiliorism in favor of equiprobabilism.",
