    body: "Fundamental option theory, developed by Karl Rahner and others, proposes that a person's moral status before God is determined by a deep, core orientation (fundamental option) toward or against God, not primarily by individual acts. While Catholic theology affirms that the deepest dispositions of the heart matter, Veritatis Splendor (65-70) critiques versions of this theory that deny individual acts can constitute mortal sin. John Paul II insisted that specific, freely chosen acts of grave matter with full knowledge and consent can indeed rupture one's relationship with God, regardless of one's general orientation. The fundamental option cannot be separated from concrete moral choices.",
