    body: "Veritatis Splendor (79-83) reaffirms the traditional teaching that certain acts are intrinsece malum — evil by their very object (the finis operis), irrespective of the agent's intention or the surrounding circumstances. This means no good end can justify performing an intrinsically evil act (the end does not justify the means). The moral object is not merely the physical behavior but the freely chosen kind of action as understood by reason. Examples include direct killing of the innocent, torture, adultery, and lying. This doctrine stands against consequentialism and proportionalism, which would allow these acts if the overall consequences or proportion of goods seemed favorable.",
