    oneLiner: "The moral distinction between sharing in the evil intention of another's wrongdoing (formal cooperation, always sinful) and contributing to it without sharing the intention (material cooperation, sometimes permissible).",
    body: "Formal cooperation means one shares the wrongdoer's evil intention — this is always morally impermissible. Material cooperation means one contributes to another's evil act without intending the evil — this may be permissible if there is a proportionately grave reason and if the cooperation is not immediate (i.e., one does not perform the evil act itself). Material cooperation is further divided into immediate (participating directly in the evil act) and mediate (providing assistance that the evildoer uses). The more remote the cooperation, the less serious the reason needed to justify it. This framework is essential in bioethics, business ethics, and political participation.",
