    oneLiner: "The moral principle that an action with both a good and a bad effect may be permissible if four strict conditions are met.",
    body: "The principle of double effect, rooted in St. Thomas Aquinas (ST II-II, q.64, a.7), governs situations where a single act produces both a good effect and a harmful side effect. Four conditions must be met simultaneously: (1) the act itself must be morally good or indifferent; (2) the agent must intend only the good effect, merely tolerating the bad; (3) the bad effect must not be the means of producing the good effect; (4) there must be a proportionately grave reason for tolerating the bad effect. If any condition fails, the act is impermissible. This principle is widely applied in medical ethics, just war theory, and cases of self-defense.",
