    body: "Catholic moral theology teaches that every person has a duty to preserve life using ordinary (proportionate) means but is not obligated to use extraordinary (disproportionate) means. What counts as ordinary or extraordinary depends on the patient's total situation: the treatment's effectiveness, its pain and cost, and the patient's overall condition. A treatment that is ordinary for one patient may be extraordinary for another. This teaching, developed by 16th-century Dominican moralists and affirmed by Pius XII in 1957 and by the CDF's Declaration on Euthanasia (1980), guides end-of-life decisions without endorsing either euthanasia or vitalism.",
