    body: "In traditional Catholic moral theology, proportionate reason is a legitimate component of double-effect reasoning: one needs a sufficiently serious reason to tolerate a foreseen but unintended bad effect. However, the proportionalist school (associated with Peter Knauer, Louis Janssens, and Richard McCormick) reinterpreted proportionate reason as the decisive factor in determining the morality of any act, arguing that no act is intrinsically evil if a proportionate reason exists. Veritatis Splendor (75-77) condemned proportionalism as incompatible with Catholic moral teaching because it effectively denies intrinsically evil acts by subordinating moral absolutes to a cost-benefit analysis.",
